Back in August, right in the middle of our move, we lost our kitty to a rare autoimmune disease. I didn't talk about it much on social media but it was incredibly traumatic for the whole family. Immediately afterwards I said what I think we all do following the loss of a precious pet: "Never again." 

Since then I've had a kitty shaped hole in my heart. Lately I've been thinking about filling it but I'd be lying if I said I wasn't nervous about setting myself up for the same heartbreak in the future. With the joys of love come the inevitability of loss. Does future grief diminish the happiness love brings to life? Winne the Pooh said it best: "How lucky I am to have something that makes saying goodbye so hard."

To all of you who have loved and lost a pet, I hope your memories continue to bring you a spark of happiness when your heart recalls them.

"Even if we’re apart… I’ll always be with you." - Winnie the Pooh

Have you ever made onigiri? It's been a while since I've made some myself but I keep seeing them pop up on TikTok. Watching the rice get crispy never fails to stir my appetite!

I haven't had much time (or energy, let's be totally honest!) to cook lately so drawing onigiri and making onigiri stickers will have to do for now 😋 This not-so-little sticker will be available in my shops during the next update! 

My favorite onigiri filling has to be umeboshi or pickled plum-but that's probably no surprise to you! I am a salty snack kinda girl. Have you tried onigiri? If so what's your favorite filling?

If you caught my Story, you already know the scoop. 😅 So, recently, I had to bid farewell to my beloved drawn portrait as my profile picture. The reason? Well, I applied for that coveted Meta verified status to ensure the safety of my account. Safety first, right? 🛡️⁠
⁠
While I'm not entirely thrilled about having a photo as my profile picture (especially not this one 😅), being verified is crucial for safeguarding my creative space. 🎨🌈 I've heard horror stories from fellow artists, like @thatoneartistnrae, who struggled for months to regain access or who lost their accounts entirely without recourse. There are even insurance plans you can purchase from 3rd parties to protect against loss of income from such disasters.⁠
⁠
Now, here's the kicker: I can't change my profile picture for an entire month! Yup, stuck with this rather serious-looking one till late August. But hey, maybe it serves as a PSA for all my fellow creators and artists out there. 📢 Don't apply if you don't want your full name and picture on your profile! And remember, you can't swap out your photo more than once per month. 🔒⁠
⁠
On the bright side, it's pretty hilarious to see the contrast between my happy, cheerful art and my new "serious" profile picture. My "creating smiles" tagline next this 😐 has me 💀⁠
⁠
As promised, I wanted to share the brand new portrait I worked so diligently on, even if I won't be using it for my profile. It's a bit of a departure from my usual style, and I'm still pondering if I should incorporate it into my packaging. 🎁 Decisions, decisions... ⭐️⁠
⁠
Thank you all for your incredible support, for laughing along with me, and for those of you who reached out to say you'd like to see even more of the face behind the art-although not necessarily like this 👁👄👁⁠

This is Boba, my 8 month old ragdoll kitten, who has brought immense joy and love into our lives. Just recently, we were dealt a devastating blow: Boba has been diagnosed with Feline Infectious Peritonitis (FIP). Until recently, FIP was considered a death sentence, but there's a glimmer of hope thanks to advancements in medical science.

His treatment journey entails a rigorous 84-day regimen of antiviral injections. Throughout this period, he will undergo scheduled ultrasounds and bloodwork at day 30, 60, and 80 milestones. If we get encouraging results, Boba will transition into a three-month "observation" phase, featuring monthly veterinary check-ups to closely monitor his condition.

While we're blessed to have excellent pet insurance, it doesn't provide full coverage for every aspect of his treatment. The most significant gap is the cost of the antiviral injections, which are essential but unfortunately not covered by our policy.

Even if you can't contribute financially, sharing this campaign with your network would mean the world to us. We will keep everyone updated on Boba's journey, every step of the way.

Who's ready for a food fact? 💡🤓⁠
⁠
Did you know sushi was sold as street-side snack food?⁠
⁠
Picture this: It's September of 1923 in Edo, which we now know as Tokyo. Hundreds of sushi carts, charmingly called 'yatai,' were scattered around the city, offering delectable delights to passersby. 😋🍣⁠
⁠
But then, the Great Kanto Earthquake struck Tokyo, and the landscape changed dramatically. Land prices plummeted, creating a unique opportunity for our sushi-loving vendors. They decided to seize the moment, buy indoor spaces, and move their beloved carts indoors. And thus, the sushi-ya, dedicated sushi restaurants, were born all across Japan's vibrant capital city. 🏙️🍱⁠
⁠
Fast forward to the 1950s, and sushi had evolved from humble street food to an exclusive indoor dining experience. Quite the transformation, wouldn't you agree? 🕰️🍽️⁠
⁠

The last month has been difficult. I ended up in the ER. What I thought would be a brief visit (it was) turned into a long recovery. All the while I kept telling myself I'd feel better soon. Days turned into weeks and the crushing weight of Instagram messages, Etsy conversations, and emails has taken a bigger toll than the physical repercussions of that visit.

Constantly feeling like I'm failing at juggling my health and the new position I hold at my company, in addition to my art and business, is chipping away at my mental state.

Here's how I'm going to work on that and what it means for you:

I am not even close to finishing this month's theme (Basil's Bath Time). Yep, we're at the end of the month and it's 10% done. Realistically, given my health, I won't be in a position to ship the November subscription till the end of December, possibly early January.

If you don't want to wait that long for the November theme, and I wouldn't blame you, please contact Chad via email at chad@kitschykawaii.com and request a refund.

Chad and my mom have been amazing at shipping, packing, and answering emails and conversations-all the while caring for my physical needs. But they've no doubt made mistakes, even trying their best.

If you need customer support, please reach out to Chad directly via that email. If you previously reached out to me via my personal email or through DM, I encourage you to re-send your message to him. He's wearing a lot of hats right now and I don't want him to miss your request.

I will be pausing the Club beginning in December so I can take a breath, heal, and find my happy again.

I created Kitschy Kawaii to bring joy to others. When I can't keep my obligations to you, I feel a deep sense of failure. But at this very moment, I need to care for my own health, physically and mentally.

To all of you who struggle with your health, mental and physical, you're not alone. 💙
